  "prompt": "Can a woman get pregnant a few days before her period and still have period?",
  "response": "While it is less likely, a woman can theoretically get pregnant a few days before her period, though the probability is low. This is because ovulation typically occurs about 12\u201316 days *before* the start of the next period, and sperm can survive in the female reproductive tract for up to 5 days. If ovulation happens later than usual in the menstrual cycle, conception could occur closer to the expected period.\n\nIf fertilization and implantation occur, the woman may still experience some light bleeding (often mistaken for a period), which is actually implantation bleeding. This happens when the fertilized egg attaches to the uterine lining, usually around 6\u201312 days after ovulation. However, this is not a true menstrual period.\n\nIn most cases, if a woman becomes pregnant, her period will not occur. If she has what seems like a normal period, pregnancy is unlikely but not impossible, as some women may experience light bleeding in early pregnancy. A pregnancy test or an appointment with a healthcare provider can provide clarity.",
